<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_6:_2.2_The_Profit_Equation">Notes for Week 6: 2.2 The Profit Equation</span></h2>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Economic_Profits_vs_Accounting_Profits">Economic Profits vs Accounting Profits</span></h1>
<p><strong>Accounting Profits</strong> are <em>Revenue</em> minus <em>Operating Costs</em> and <strong>Economic Profits</strong> are <em>Revenue</em> minus <em>Operating Costs</em> minus <em>Opportunity Costs</em>.</p>
<p>This distinction is very important.</p>
<p>The example in the video showed:
<ul><li> Salary         = $100
</li><li> Revenue        = $200
</li><li> Operating Cost = $100</p>
</li></ul>

<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Accounting_Profits">Accounting Profits</span></h2>
<p>Using the formula Profits = R - TC  ($200-$100=$100)
<ul><li> In this case the total costs did not include opportunity costs.</p>
</li></ul>

<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Economic_Profits">Economic Profits</span></h2>
<p>Using the formula Profits = R - TC  ($200-$100-$100=$0)
<ul><li> In this case the total costs included the opportunity costs as well.</p>
</li></ul>


